      <section xml:id="sec-sets-functions"><title>Useful Tools on Sets and Functions</title>

        <blockquote>
          <p>
            <q>
              The excellence of a thing related to its proper function.
            </q>
          </p>
          <attribution>Aristotle</attribution>
        </blockquote>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-sets"><title>Properties of Sets</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.1"><title>Distributive laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A \cap (\cup_\alpha B_\alpha ) = \cup_\alpha (A \cap B_\alpha )</m> and <m>A \cup (\cap_\alpha B_\alpha ) = \cap_\alpha (A \cup B_\alpha )</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.2"><title>De Morgan's laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A\setminus (\cup_\alpha B_\alpha ) = \cap_\alpha (A\setminus B_\alpha )</m> and <m>A\setminus (\cap_\alpha B_\alpha ) = \cup_\alpha (A\setminus B_\alpha )</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <p>
            Template to prove two sets are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.3"><title>Power Set</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The <em>power set</em> <m>\cP (S)</m> of a set <m>S</m> is the set of all subsets of <m>S</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Discussion of standard mathematical conventions for notation
            Notation for indices: <m>i,j,k,m,n</m> for finite or countably many indices, <m>\alpha,\beta,\dots </m> for arbitrarily many indices.
            Notation for sets, elements of sets, and sets of sets: Small letters <m>a,b,c,p,q,x,y,z</m> for elements of sets, capital letters <m>A,B,C,X,Y,Z</m> for sets, calligraphic capital letters <m>\cB,\cC,\cT,\cU </m> for collections of sets.
          </p>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-functions"><title>Properties of functions</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For a function <m>f: G \to H</m>, the set <m>G</m> is the <em>domain</em>, the set <m>H</m> is the <em>codomain</em>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Template to define a function
          </p>

          <p>
            Template to prove two functions are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A function <m>f: G \to H</m> is <em>well-defined</em> if whenever <m>g,g' \in G</m> and <m>g = g'</m>, then <m>f(g) = f(g')</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              All functions are well-defined.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.8">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X \to Y</m> be a function.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The function <m>f</m> is <em>one-to-one</em> (also called an <em>injection</em> and denoted <m>f: X \into  Y</m>) if whenever <m>x,x' \in X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x = x'</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The function <m>f</m> is <em>onto</em> (also called a <em>surjection</em> and denoted <m>f: X \onto  Y</m>) if for every <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m>, there is an <m>x</m> in <m>X</m> with <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The function <m>f</m> is a <em>bijection</em> if <m>f</m> is both one-to-one and onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The function <m>f</m> is <em>invertible</em> if there is a function <m>g:Y \to X</m> such that <m>f \circ g = 1_Y</m> and <m>g \circ f = 1_X</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.9">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>a: G \to H, b: H \to K</m>, and <m>c: K \to L</m> be functions. 
                Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are one-to-one then ba is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is one-to-one then a is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are onto then <m>ba</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is onto then <m>b</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>a</m> is a bijection if and only if <m>a</m> is invertible.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X \to Y</m> be a function.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The <em>image</em> of a subset <m>A</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>f(A) := \{f(a) | a \in A\}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The <em>preimage</em> of a subset <m>B</m> of <m>Y</m> is <m>f\inv(B) := \{g | g \in X and f(g) \in B\}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The <em>image</em> of <m>f</m> is <m>f(X)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-pan"><title>PAN = <q>Preimages are nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X \to Y</m>, <m>E \sse E' \sse Y</m>, and <m>E_\alpha \sse Y</m> for all <m>\alpha </m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E) \sse f\inv(E')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(\cup_\alpha E\alpha ) = \cup_\alpha f\inv(E_\alpha )</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(\cap_\alpha E_\alpha ) = \cap_\alpha f\inv(E_\alpha )</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E'\setminus E) = f\inv(E')\setminus f\inv(E)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-iasn"><title>IASN = <q>Images are sometimes nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X \to Y, C \sse C' \sse X</m>, and <m>C_\alpha \sse X for all \alpha </m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C) \sse f(C')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(\cup \alpha C_\alpha ) = \cup \alpha f(C_\alpha )</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(\cap_\alpha C_\alpha ) \sse \cap_\alpha f(C_\alpha )</m>. 
                      If moreover <m>f</m> is injective, then <m>f(\cap_\alpha C_\alpha ) = \cap_\alpha f(C_\alpha )</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C'\setminus C) \supseteq f(C')\setminus f(C)</m>. 
                      If moreover <m>f</m> is injective, then <m>f(C'\setminus C) = f(C')\setminus f(C)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.13">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X \to Y</m>. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>A \sse X</m>, then <m>A \sse f\inv(f(A))</m>; 
                      if moreover <m>f</m> is injective then <m>A = f\inv(f(A))</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>B \sse Y</m> then <m>f(f\inv(B)) \sse B</m>; 
                      if moreover <m>f</m> is surjective then <m>f(f\inv(B)) = B</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-constructions"><title>Constructions of new sets from old ones, and the associated functions</title>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subsets"><title>Subsets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.15">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A</m> be a set. 
                  A <em>subset</em> of <m>A</m> is a set of some (possibly none, possibly all, possibly neither) of the elements of <m>A</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.16">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>B \sse A</m>. 
                  The <em>inclusion map</em> is the function <m>i:B \to A</m> defined by <m>i(b) = b</m> for all <m>b \in B</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.17">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>B \sse A</m> and <m>i:B \to A</m> is the inclusion, then <m>i</m> is an injection.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-products"><title>Product sets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.20">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A, B</m>, and <m>A_\alpha </m> for all <m>\alpha \in J</m> be sets. 
                  The <em>Cartesian product</em> <m>A \times B := \{(a,b) | a \in A, b \in B\} \text{ and }\prod_{\alpha \in J} A_\alpha := \{(a_\alpha )_{\alpha \in J} | a_\alpha \in A_\alpha \}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.21">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_\alpha </m> for all <m>\alpha \in J</m> be sets and let <m>\beta\in J</m>. 
                  The <em>projection map</em> <m>p_\beta : \prod_{\alpha \in J} A_\alpha \to A_\beta </m> is defined by <m>p_\beta ((a_\alpha )_{\alpha \in J}) = a_\beta  \text{ for all }(a_\alpha )_{\alpha \in J} \in \prod_{\alpha \in J} A_\alpha </m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.22">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_\alpha </m> for all <m>\alpha \in J</m> be sets, let <m>\beta \in J</m>, and for each <m>\alpha \in J\setminus \{\beta \}</m>, let <m>b_\alpha \in A_\alpha </m>. 
                  The associated <em>product inclusion map</em> <m>i_\beta : A_\beta \to \prod_{\alpha \in J} A_\alpha </m> is defined for each <m>a \in A_\beta </m> by <m>i_\beta (a) := (a_\alpha )_{\alpha \in J}</m>, where <m>a_\beta  := a</m> and <m>a_\alpha := b_\alpha \text{ for all }\alpha \in J\setminus \{\beta \}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.23">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Projection maps are surjections. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Product inclusion maps are injections.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-1.24">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>A \sse G</m> and <m>B \sse H</m>, then <m>A \times B \sse G \times H</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>

            <axiom xml:id="axiom-choice"><title>Axiom of Choice</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>A_\alpha \ne \es </m> for all <m>\alpha \in J</m>, then <m>\prod_{\alpha \in J} A_\alpha \ne \es </m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </axiom>
            
          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quotients"><title>Quotient sets and equivalence relations</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.27">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  An <em>equivalence relation</em> <m>\sim </m> on a set <m>X</m> is a subset <m>S</m> of <m>X \times X</m> (where <m>(a,b) \in S</m> is written <m>a \sim b</m>) that satisfies the following for all <m>a,b,c</m> in <m>X</m>: 
                  <ol>
                    <li><title>Reflexive</title>
                      <p>
                        <m>a \sim a</m>,
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li><title>Symmetric</title>
                      <p>
                        <m>a \sim b</m> implies <m>b \sim a</m>, and 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li><title>Transitive</title>
                      <p>
                        <m>a \sim b</m> and <m>b \sim c</m> implies <m>a \sim c</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  The <em>equivalence class</em> of an element <m>a</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>[a] := \{b | b \sim a\}</m>.
                  The notation <m>X/\sim </m> denotes the set of equivalence classes, also called the <em>quotient</em> of <m>X</m> with respect to <m>\sim </m>.
                  The function <m>q:X \to X/\sim </m> defined by <m>q(p) := [p]</m> for all <m>p \in X</m> is called the <em>equivalence map</em>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.28">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A <em>partition</em> of a set <m>X</m> is a collection of nonempty disjoint subsets of <m>X</m> whose union is <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.29">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set. 
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>\sim </m> is an equivalence relation on <m>G</m>, then <m>X/\sim </m> is a partition of <m>X</m>. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>\cC </m> is a partition of <m>X</m>, and <m>T = \{(x,y) \in X \times X | x,y \text{ are in the same element of }\cC \}</m>, then <m>T</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.30">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>f: X \to Y</m> be a function, and let <m>\sim = \{(p,p') \in X \times X | f(p) = f(p')\}</m>. 
                  Then <m>\sim </m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.31"><title>FBT = Function Building Theorem for quotient sets</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\sim </m> be an equivalence relation on a set <m>X</m>, and let <m>f: X \to Y</m> be a function satisfying the property that whenever <m>x,x' \in X</m> and <m>x \sim x'</m> then <m>f(x) = f(x')</m>. 
                  Then:
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        There is a well-defined function <m>g:X/\sim \to Y</m> defined by <m>g([x]) = f(x)</m> for all <m>[x]</m> in <m>X/\sim </m>; that is, <m>g \circ q = f</m>, where <m>q</m> is the equivalence map.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is onto, then <m>g</m> is onto.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> also satisfies the property that whenever <m>x,x' \in X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x \sim x'</m>, then <m>g</m> is one-to-one.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <p>
              Template for proving a well-defined function with domain <m>X/\sim </m>.
            </p>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.32">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set and let <m>S</m> be a subset of <m>X \times X</m>. 
                  The <em>equivalence relation on <m>X</m> generated by</em> <m>S</m> is the intersection of all of the equivalence relations on <m>X</m> that contain <m>S</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
          </subsubsection>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-cardinality"><title>Cardinality</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.34">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A set <m>X</m> is <em>finite</em> if there is a bijection <m>X \to \{1,\dots,n\}</m> for some natural number <m>n</m>, or <m>X</m> is empty. 
                      In this case the number <m>n</m> is called the <em>cardinality</em> of <m>X</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A set <m>X</m> is <em>infinite</em> if <m>X</m> is not finite. 
                      A set <m>X</m> is <em>countable</em> if there is an injection <m>X \into \N </m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.35">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a set.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The following are equivalent: 
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>X</m> is finite. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is an onto function <m>\{1,\dots,n\} \onto  X</m> for some <m>n \in \N </m>. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is a one-to-one function <m>X \into \{1,\dots,n\}</m> for some <m>n \in \N </m>.
                          </p>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The following are equivalent: 
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>X</m> is infinite. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is an onto function <m>X \onto \N </m>. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is a one-to-one function <m>\N \into  X</m>.
                          </p>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The following are equivalent: 
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>X</m> is countable. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is an onto function <m>\N \to X</m>. 
                          </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                          <p>
                            There is an injection <m>X \into \N </m>.
                          </p>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.36">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of finite sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, finite unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of countable sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, countable unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>
                    
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-bounds"><title>Upper and lower bound properties of <m>\N</m>  and <m>\R</m> </title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.39">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      An <em>upper bound</em> for a subset <m>A \sse \R </m> is a real number <m>r \in \R </m> satisfying <m>a \leq r</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A <em>lower bound</em> for a subset <m>A \sse \R </m> is a real number <m>s \in \R </m> satisfying <m>s \leq a</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li><title>Least upper bound property of <m>\R </m></title>
                    <p>
                      If <m>A \sse \R </m> and <m>A</m> has an upper bound, then <m>A</m> has a least upper bound. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li><title>Greatest lower bound property of <m>\R </m></title>
                    <p>
                      If <m>A \sse \R </m> and <m>A</m> has a lower bound, then <m>A</m> has a greatest lower bound.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.41"><title>Archimedean property of <m>\N </m></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\N </m> has no upper bound in <m>\R </m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>
        
      </section>
      
